erly, the development of a retirement lifestyle, and pensions and politics. "[Costa's] major contribution is to show that, even without Social Security and Medicare, retirement would have expanded dramatically."—Robert J. Samuelson, New Republic "An important book on a topic which has become popular with historians and is of major significance to politicians and economists."—Margaret Walsh, Business History  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAging -- Government policy -- United States. 0aOld age pensions -- United States. 0aOlder people -- United States -- Economic conditions. 0aOlder people -- United States -- Social conditions. 0aRetirement -- United States -- History. 0aSocial sciences. 0aSocial security -- United States. 0aUnited States -- Economic policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aretirement, labor, employment, aging, masculinity, health, income, work, disease, older workers, elderly, lifestyle, pension, politics, living arrangements, medicare, social security, nonfiction, economics, government, policy, family, leisure, legislation, disability, privatization, funding, finance, money, age discrimination act.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226116228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226116228/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles